Her encounter with a kitsune only reinforces this negative side. But if a kitsune like Katsuo could change her, he would have to make a sacrifice. As a natural and sacred being, he overrides all human morality; he only exploits her. But if he wants to change this person, he must get involved. And for a kitsune, this compromises the mechanism of their tails, and when their fifth tail splits, they will likely no longer be a “good kitsune” but a “bad kitsune.” This is a risk for a kitsune to take, but thanks to their exceptional skill, Katsuo can now undertake such missions without risking changing their path. The kitsune is a bodhisattva. They possess important spiritual qualities, such as the “four divine abodes” (brahmavihāras): loving-kindness (maitrī), compassion (karuṇā), empathic joy (muditā), and equanimity (upekṣā), as well as the various bodhisattva “perfections” (pāramitās), including prajñāpāramitā (“transcendent knowledge” or “perfection of wisdom”) and skill (upāya). For now, he is a "caryās," possessing the entire "Bodhipakkhiyādhammā" and following the rules of the eight paths:
The Noble Eightfold Path

